Seven near-simultaneous bomb blasts in Jaipur killed 80 and injured 200, sparking condemnation from global leaders.
The attacks, described as terror acts, prompted heightened security measures in Rajasthan and neighboring regions.
While officials refrained from directly accusing Pakistan, suspicions lingered on foreign connections to the perpetrators.
The tragic event reignited concerns over religious tensions and the ongoing battle against terrorism in India.
International support poured in, with countries like the United States, Britain, and France offering solidarity and assistance in combating such heinous acts.
